# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: homotopy-type-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] In mathematics, a **constructive proof** is a method of proof that demonstrates the existence of a mathematical object by creating or providing a method for creating the object.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] This is in contrast to a **non-constructive proof** (also known as an **existence proof** or *pure existence theorem*), which proves the existence of a particular kind of object without providing an example.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] For avoiding confusion with the stronger concept that follows, such a constructive proof is sometimes called an **effective proof**.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] A **constructive proof** may also refer to the stronger concept of a proof that is valid in constructive mathematics.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] Constructivism is a mathematical philosophy that rejects all proof methods that involve the existence of objects that are not explicitly built.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] This excludes, in particular, the use of the law of the excluded middle, the axiom of infinity, and the axiom of choice.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] Constructivism also induces a different meaning for some terminology (for example, the term "or" has a stronger meaning in constructive mathematics than in classical).
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] Some non-constructive proofs show that if a certain proposition is false, a contradiction ensues; consequently the proposition must be true (proof by contradiction).
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] However, the principle of explosion (*ex falso quodlibet*) has been accepted in some varieties of constructive mathematics, including intuitionism.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] Until the end of 19th century, all mathematical proofs were essentially constructive.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] The first non-constructive constructions appeared with Georg Cantor’s theory of infinite sets, and the formal definition of real numbers.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] The first use of non-constructive proofs for solving previously considered problems seems to be Hilbert's Nullstellensatz and Hilbert's basis theorem.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] From a philosophical point of view, the former is especially interesting, as implying the existence of a well specified object.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] Such a non-constructive existence theorem was such a surprise for mathematicians of that time that one of them, Paul Gordan, wrote: *"this is not mathematics, it is theology*".
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] Twenty five years later, Grete Hermann provided an algorithm for computing $g_{1},\ldots ,g_{k},$ which is not a constructive proof in the strong sense, as she used Hilbert's result.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] She proved that, if $g_{1},\ldots ,g_{k}$ exist, they can be found with degrees less than $2^{2^{n}}$ .
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] First consider the theorem that there are an infinitude of prime numbers.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] But a common way of simplifying Euclid's proof postulates that, contrary to the assertion in the theorem, there are only a finite number of them, in which case there is a largest one, denoted *n*.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] Then consider the number *n*! + 1 (1 + the product of the first *n* numbers).
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] Either this number is prime, or all of its prime factors are greater than *n*.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] Without establishing a specific prime number, this proves that one exists that is greater than *n*, contrary to the original postulate.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] Now consider the theorem "there exist irrational numbers a and b such that $a^{b}$ is rational." This theorem can be proven by using both a constructive proof, and a non-constructive proof.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] At its core, this proof is non-constructive because it relies on the statement "Either *q* is rational or it is irrational"—an instance of the law of excluded middle, which is not valid within a constructive proof.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] The non-constructive proof does not construct an example *a* and *b*; it merely gives a number of possibilities (in this case, two mutually exclusive possibilities) and shows that one of them—but does not show *which* one—must yield the desired example.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] As it turns out, ${\sqrt {2}}^{\sqrt {2}}$ is irrational because of the Gelfond–Schneider theorem, but this fact is irrelevant to the correctness of the non-constructive proof.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] The square root of 2 is irrational, and 3 is rational. $\log _{2}9$ is also irrational: if it were equal to $m \over n$ , then, by the properties of logarithms, 9*n* would be equal to 2*m*, but the former is odd, and the latter is even.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] A more substantial example is the graph minor theorem.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] A consequence of this theorem is that a graph can be drawn on the torus if, and only if, none of its minors belong to a certain finite set of "forbidden minors".
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] However, the proof of the existence of this finite set is not constructive, and the forbidden minors are not actually specified.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] In constructive mathematics, a statement may be disproved by giving a counterexample, as in classical mathematics.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] However, it is also possible to give a **Brouwerian counterexample** to show that the statement is non-constructive.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] This sort of counterexample shows that the statement implies some principle that is known to be non-constructive.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] If it can be proved constructively that the statement implies some principle that is not constructively provable, then the statement itself cannot be constructively provable.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] For example, a particular statement may be shown to imply the law of the excluded middle.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] An example of a Brouwerian counterexample of this type is Diaconescu's theorem, which shows that the full axiom of choice is non-constructive in systems of constructive set theory, since the axiom of choice implies the law of excluded middle in such systems.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] The field of constructive reverse mathematics develops this idea further by classifying various principles in terms of "how nonconstructive" they are, by showing they are equivalent to various fragments of the law of the excluded middle.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] Brouwer also provided "weak" counterexamples.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] Such counterexamples do not disprove a statement, however; they only show that, at present, no constructive proof of the statement is known.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] One weak counterexample begins by taking some unsolved problem of mathematics, such as Goldbach's conjecture, which asks whether every even natural number larger than 4 is the sum of two primes.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] For each *n*, the value of *a*(*n*) can be determined by exhaustive search, and so *a* is a well defined sequence, constructively.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] Moreover, because *a* is a Cauchy sequence with a fixed rate of convergence, *a* converges to some real number α, according to the usual treatment of real numbers in constructive mathematics.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] Several facts about the real number α can be proved constructively.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] Because no such proof is known, the quoted statement must also not have a known constructive proof.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] However, it is entirely possible that Goldbach's conjecture may have a constructive proof (as we do not know at present whether it does), in which case the quoted statement would have a constructive proof as well, albeit one that is unknown at present.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] The main practical use of weak counterexamples is to identify the "hardness" of a problem.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] For example, the counterexample just shown shows that the quoted statement is "at least as hard to prove" as Goldbach's conjecture.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/constructive-proof] Weak counterexamples of this sort are often related to the limited principle of omniscience.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] In mathematical logic and computer science, **homotopy type theory** (**HoTT**) includes various lines of development of intuitionistic type theory, based on the interpretation of types as objects to which the intuition of (abstract) homotopy theory applies.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] There is a large overlap between the work referred to as homotopy type theory, and that called the univalent foundations project.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] Although neither is precisely delineated, and the terms are sometimes used interchangeably, the choice of usage also sometimes corresponds to differences in viewpoint and emphasis.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] As such, this article may not represent the views of all researchers in the fields equally.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] This kind of variability is unavoidable when a field is in rapid flux.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] At one time, the idea that types in intensional type theory with their identity types could be regarded as groupoids was mathematical folklore.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] It was first made precise semantically in the 1994 paper of Martin Hofmann and Thomas Streicher called "The groupoid model refutes uniqueness of identity proofs", in which they showed that intensional type theory had a model in the category of groupoids.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] This was the first truly "homotopical" model of type theory, albeit only "1-dimensional" (the traditional models in the category of sets being homotopically 0-dimensional).
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] Their follow-up paper foreshadowed several later developments in homotopy type theory.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] For instance, they noted that the groupoid model satisfies a rule they called "universe extensionality", which is none other than the restriction to 1-types of the *univalence axiom* that Vladimir Voevodsky proposed 10 years later.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] The first higher-dimensional models of intensional type theory were constructed by Steve Awodey and his student Michael Warren in 2005 using Quillen model categories.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] These results were first presented in public at the conference FMCS 2006 at which Warren gave a talk titled "Homotopy models of intensional type theory", which also served as his thesis prospectus (the dissertation committee present were Awodey, Nicola Gambino and Alex Simpson).
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] A summary is contained in Warren's thesis prospectus abstract.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] Related ideas were discussed in the talks by Steve Awodey, "Type theory of higher-dimensional categories", and Thomas Streicher, "Identity types vs. weak omega-groupoids: some ideas, some problems".
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] At the same conference Benno van den Berg gave a talk titled "Types as weak omega-categories" where he outlined the ideas that later became the subject of a joint paper with Richard Garner.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] All early constructions of higher dimensional models had to deal with the problem of coherence typical of models of dependent type theory, and various solutions were developed.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] One such was given in 2009 by Voevodsky, another in 2010 by van den Berg and Garner.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] A general solution, building on Voevodsky's construction, was eventually given by Lumsdaine and Warren in 2014.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] At the PSSL86 in 2007 Awodey gave a talk titled "Homotopy type theory" (this was the first public usage of that term, which was coined by Awodey).
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] Awodey and Warren summarized their results in the paper "Homotopy theoretic models of identity types", which was posted on the ArXiv preprint server in 2007 and published in 2009; a more detailed version appeared in Warren's thesis "Homotopy theoretic aspects of constructive type theory" in 2008.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] At about the same time, Vladimir Voevodsky was independently investigating type theory in the context of the search of a language for practical formalization of mathematics.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] In September 2006 he posted to the Types mailing list "A very short note on homotopy lambda calculus", which sketched the outlines of a type theory with dependent products, sums and universes and of a model of this type theory in Kan simplicial sets.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] It began by saying "The homotopy λ-calculus is a hypothetical (at the moment) type system" and ended with "At the moment much of what I said above is at the level of conjectures.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] Even the definition of the model of TS in the homotopy category is non-trivial" referring to the complex coherence issues that were not resolved until 2009.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] This note included a syntactic definition of "equality types" that were claimed to be interpreted in the model by path-spaces, but did not consider Per Martin-Löf's rules for identity types.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] It also stratified the universes by homotopy dimension in addition to size, an idea that later was mostly discarded.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] On the syntactic side, Benno van den Berg conjectured in 2006 that the tower of identity types of a type in intensional type theory should have the structure of an ω-category, and indeed a ω-groupoid, in the "globular, algebraic" sense of Michael Batanin.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] The concept of a univalent fibration was introduced by Voevodsky in early 2006.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] However, because of the insistence of all presentations of the Martin-Löf type theory on the property that the identity types, in the empty context, may contain only reflexivity, Voevodsky did not recognize until 2009 that these identity types can be used in combination with the univalent universes.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] In particular, the idea that univalence can be introduced simply by adding an axiom to the existing Martin-Löf type theory appeared only in 2009.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] Also in 2009, Voevodsky worked out more of the details of a model of type theory in Kan complexes, and observed that the existence of a universal Kan fibration could be used to resolve the coherence problems for categorical models of type theory.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] Bousfield, that this universal fibration was univalent: the associated fibration of pairwise homotopy equivalences between the fibers is equivalent to the paths-space fibration of the base.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] To formulate univalence as an axiom Voevodsky found a way to define "equivalences" syntactically that had the important property that the type representing the statement "f is an equivalence" was (under the assumption of function extensionality) (-1)-truncated (i.e. contractible if inhabited).
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] This enabled him to give a *syntactic* statement of univalence, generalizing Hofmann and Streicher's "universe extensionality" to higher dimensions.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] He was also able to use these definitions of equivalences and contractibility to start developing significant amounts of "synthetic homotopy theory" in the proof assistant Rocq (previously known as *Coq*); this formed the basis of the library later called "Foundations" and eventually "UniMath".
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] Unification of the various threads began in February 2010 with an informal meeting at Carnegie Mellon University, where Voevodsky presented his model in Kan complexes, and his version of Rocq, to a group including Awodey, Warren, Lumsdaine, Robert Harper, Dan Licata, Michael Shulman, and others.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] This meeting produced the outlines of a proof (by Warren, Lumsdaine, Licata, and Shulman) that every homotopy equivalence is an equivalence (in Voevodsky's good coherent sense), based on the idea from category theory of improving equivalences to adjoint equivalences.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] Soon afterwards, Voevodsky proved that the univalence axiom implies function extensionality.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] The next pivotal event was a mini-workshop at the Mathematical Research Institute of Oberwolfach in March 2011 organized by Steve Awodey, Richard Garner, Per Martin-Löf, and Vladimir Voevodsky, titled "The homotopy interpretation of constructive type theory".
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] One of the most important things to come out of the Oberwolfach meeting was the basic idea of higher inductive types, due to Lumsdaine, Shulman, Bauer, and Warren.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] Soon after the Oberwolfach workshop, the *Homotopy Type Theory website and blog* was established, and the subject began to be popularized under that name.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] An idea of some of the important progress during this period can be obtained from the blog history.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] The phrase "univalent foundations" is agreed by all to be closely related to homotopy type theory, but not everyone uses it in the same way.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] It was originally used by Vladimir Voevodsky to refer to his vision of a foundational system for mathematics in which the basic objects are homotopy types, based on a type theory satisfying § the univalence axiom, and formalized in a computer proof assistant.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] For instance, the subject of the IAS special year was officially given as "univalent foundations", although a lot of the work done there focused on semantics and metatheory in addition to foundations.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] The book produced by participants in the IAS program was titled "Homotopy type theory: Univalent foundations of mathematics"; although this could refer to either usage, since the book only discusses HoTT as a mathematical foundation.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] In 2012–13 researchers at the Institute for Advanced Study held "A Special Year on Univalent Foundations of Mathematics".
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] The special year brought together researchers in topology, computer science, category theory, and mathematical logic.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] The program was organized by Steve Awodey, Thierry Coquand and Vladimir Voevodsky.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] During the program Peter Aczel, who was one of the participants, initiated a working group which investigated how to do type theory informally but rigorously, in a style that is analogous to ordinary mathematicians doing set theory.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] After initial experiments it became clear that this was not only possible but highly beneficial, and that a book (the so-called **HoTT Book**) could and should be written.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] Many other participants of the project then joined the effort with technical support, writing, proof reading, and offering ideas.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] Unusually for a mathematics text, it was developed collaboratively and in the open on GitHub, is released under a Creative Commons license that allows people to fork their own version of the book, and is both purchasable in print and downloadable free of charge.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] More generally, the special year was a catalyst for the development of the entire subject; the HoTT Book was only one, albeit the most visible, result.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] HoTT uses a modified version of the "propositions as types" interpretation of type theory, according to which types can also represent propositions and terms can then represent proofs.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] In HoTT, however, unlike in standard "propositions as types", a special role is played by 'mere propositions' which, roughly speaking, are those types having at most one term, up to propositional equality.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] These are more like conventional logical propositions than are general types, in that they are proof-irrelevant.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] The fundamental concept of homotopy type theory is the path.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] In HoTT, the type $a=b$ is the type of all paths from the point a to the point b .
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] (Therefore, a proof that a point a equals a point b is the same thing as a path from the point a to the point b .) For any point a , there exists a path of type $a=a$ , corresponding to the reflexive property of equality.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] A path of type $a=b$ can be inverted, forming a path of type $b=a$ , corresponding to the symmetric property of equality.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] Two paths of type $a=b$ resp. $b=c$ can be concatenated, forming a path of type $a=c$ ; this corresponds to the transitive property of equality.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] Most importantly, given a path $p:a=b$ , and a proof of some property $P(a)$ , the proof can be "transported" along the path p to yield a proof of the property $P(b)$ .
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] (Equivalently stated, an object of type $P(a)$ can be turned into an object of type $P(b)$ .) This corresponds to the substitution property of equality.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] Here, an important difference between HoTT and classical mathematics comes in.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] In classical mathematics, once the equality of two values a and b has been established, a and b may be used interchangeably thereafter, with no regard to any distinction between them.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] In homotopy type theory, however, there may be multiple different paths $a=b$ , and transporting an object along two different paths will yield two different results.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] Therefore, in homotopy type theory, when applying the substitution property, it is necessary to state which path is being used.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] In general, a "proposition" can have multiple different proofs.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] (For example, the type of all natural numbers, when considered as a proposition, has every natural number as a proof.) Even if a proposition has only one proof a , the space of paths $a=a$ may be non-trivial in some way.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] A "mere proposition" is any type which either is empty, or contains only one point with a trivial path space.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] Note that people write $a=b$ for $Id_{A}(a,b)$ , thereby leaving the type A of $a,b$ implicit.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] Do not confuse it with $id_{A}:A\to A$ , denoting the identity function on A .
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] Together with the univalence axiom below, one receives a non-circular " $\infty$ -isomorphism" expanded to identity.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] Having defined functions that are equivalences as above, one can show that there is a canonical way to turn paths to equivalences.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] which expresses that types $A,B$ that are equal are, in particular, also equivalent.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] The **univalence axiom** states that this function is itself an equivalence.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] "In other words, identity is equivalent to equivalence.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] Martín Hötzel Escardó has shown that the property of univalence is independent of Martin-Löf Type Theory (MLTT).
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] This is because type equivalence is compatible with all constructions of the type theory.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] Advocates claim that HoTT allows mathematical proofs to be translated into a computer programming language for computer proof assistants much more easily than before.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] They argue this approach increases the potential for computers to check difficult proofs.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] However, these claims are not universally accepted and many research efforts and proof assistants are not based on HoTT.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] HoTT adopts the univalence axiom, which relates the equality of logical-mathematical propositions to homotopy theory.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] An equation such as $a=b$ is a mathematical proposition in which two different symbols have the same value.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] In homotopy type theory, this is taken to mean that the two shapes which represent the values of the symbols are topologically equivalent.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] These equivalence relationships, ETH Zürich Institute for Theoretical Studies director Giovanni Felder argues, can be better formulated in homotopy theory because it is more comprehensive: Homotopy theory explains not only why "a equals b" but also how to derive this.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] In set theory, this information would have to be defined additionally, which, advocates argue, makes the translation of mathematical propositions into programming languages more difficult.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] As of 2015, intense research work was underway to model and formally analyse the computational behavior of the univalence axiom in homotopy type theory.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] Cubical type theory is one attempt to give computational content to homotopy type theory.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] However, it is believed that certain objects, such as semi-simplicial types, cannot be constructed without reference to some notion of exact equality.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] Therefore, various *two-level type theories* have been developed which partition their types into fibrant types, which respect paths, and non-fibrant types, which do not.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/higher-inductive-type] Cartesian cubical computational type theory is the first two-level type theory which gives a full computational interpretation to homotopy type theory.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/identity-type] In type theory, a branch of mathematics, the **identity type** represents the concept of equality.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/identity-type] It is also known as **propositional equality** to differentiate it from "judgemental equality".
[src:homotopy-type-theory/identity-type] Equality in type theory is a complex topic and has been the subject of research, such as the field of homotopy type theory.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/identity-type] The identity type is one of 2 different notions of equality in type theory.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/identity-type] The more fundamental notion is "judgemental equality", which is a judgement.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/identity-type] The identity type can do more than what judgemental equality can do.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/identity-type] It can be used to show "for all $x,x+1=1+x$ ", which is impossible to show with judgemental equality.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/identity-type] This is accomplished by using the eliminator (or "recursor") of the natural numbers, known as "R".
[src:homotopy-type-theory/identity-type] The "R" function lets us define a new function on the natural numbers.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/identity-type] That new function "P" is defined to be "(λ x:nat . x+1 = 1+x)".
[src:homotopy-type-theory/identity-type] The other arguments act like the parts of an induction proof.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/identity-type] The argument "PZ : P 0" becomes the base case "0+1 = 1+0", which is the term "refl nat 1".
[src:homotopy-type-theory/identity-type] The argument "PS : P n → P (S n)" becomes the inductive case.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/identity-type] Essentially, this says that when "x+1 = 1+x" has "x" replaced with a canonical value, the expression will be the same as "refl nat (x+1)".
[src:homotopy-type-theory/identity-type] The identity type is complex and is the subject of research in type theory.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/identity-type] While every version agrees on the constructor, "refl".
[src:homotopy-type-theory/identity-type] Their properties and eliminator functions differ dramatically.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/identity-type] For "extensional" versions, any identity type can be converted into a judgemental equality.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/identity-type] A computational version is known as "Axiom K" due to Thomas Streicher.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/identity-type] Martin Hofmann and Thomas Streicher refuted the idea that type theory required all terms of the identity type to be the same.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/identity-type] A popular branches of research into the identity type are homotopy type theory and its cubical type theory.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Martin-Löf designed the type theory on the principles of mathematical constructivism.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Constructivism requires any existence proof to contain a "witness".
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] So, any proof of "there exists a prime greater than 1000" must identify a specific number that is both prime and greater than 1000.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Intuitionistic type theory accomplished this design goal by internalizing the BHK interpretation.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] A useful consequence is that proofs become mathematical objects that can be examined, compared, and manipulated.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Intuitionistic type theory's type constructors were built to follow a one-to-one correspondence with logical connectives.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] For example, the logical connective called implication ( $A\implies B$ ) corresponds to the type of a function ( $A\to B$ ).
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] This correspondence is called the Curry–Howard isomorphism.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Prior type theories had also followed this isomorphism, but Martin-Löf's was the first to extend it to predicate logic by introducing dependent types.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] A type theory is a kind of mathematical ontology, or foundation, describing the fundamental objects that exist.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] In the standard foundation, set theory combined with mathematical logic, the fundamental object is the set, which is a container that contains elements.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] In type theory, the fundamental object is the term, each of which belongs to one and only one type.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Intuitionistic type theory has three finite types, which are then composed using five different type constructors.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Unlike set theories, type theories are not built on top of a logic like Frege's.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] So, each feature of the type theory does double duty as a feature of both math and logic.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] There are three finite types: The **0** type contains no terms.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] The **1** type contains one canonical term.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] The **2** type contains two canonical terms.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Because the **0** type contains no terms, it is also called the empty type.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] It is used to represent anything that cannot exist.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] It is also written $\bot$ and represents anything unprovable (that is, a proof of it cannot exist).
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] As a result, negation is defined as a function to it: $\neg A:=A\to \bot$ .
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Likewise, the **1** type contains one canonical term and represents existence.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Finally, the **2** type contains two canonical terms.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] It represents a definite choice between two values.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] It is used for Boolean values but *not* propositions.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Propositions are instead represented by particular types.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] For instance, a true proposition can be represented by the **1** type, while a false proposition can be represented by the **0** type.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] But we cannot assert that these are the only propositions, i.e. the law of excluded middle does not hold for propositions in intuitionistic type theory.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] As with typical ordered pair (or 2-tuple) types, a Σ-type can describe the Cartesian product, $A\times B$ , of two other types, A and B .
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Logically, such an ordered pair would hold a proof of A and a proof of B , so one may see such a type written as $A\wedge B$ .
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Σ-types are more powerful than typical ordered pair types because of dependent typing.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] In the ordered pair, the type of the second term can depend on the value of the first term.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] For example, the first term of the pair might be a natural number and the second term's type might be a sequence of reals of length equal to the first term.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Using set-theory terminology, this is similar to an indexed disjoint union of sets.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] In the case of the usual cartesian product, the type of the second term does not depend on the value of the first term.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] The value of the first term, n , is not dependent on the type of the second term, ${\mathbb {R} }$ .
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Σ-types can be used to build up longer dependently-typed tuples used in mathematics and the records or structs used in most programming languages.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Dependent typing allows Σ-types to serve the role of existential quantifier.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] The statement "there exists an n of type ${\mathbb {N} }$ , such that $P(n)$ is proven" becomes the type of ordered pairs where the first item is the value n of type ${\mathbb {N} }$ and the second item is a proof of $P(n)$ .
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Notice that the type of the second item (proofs of $P(n)$ ) depends on the value in the first part of the ordered pair ( n ).
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] As with typical function types, they consist of an input type and an output type.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] They are more powerful than typical function types however, in that the return type can depend on the input value.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Functions in type theory are different from set theory.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] In set theory, you look up the argument's value in a set of ordered pairs.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] In type theory, the argument is substituted into a term and then computation ("reduction") is applied to the term.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] When the output type does not depend on the input value, the function type is often simply written with a $\to$ .
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Thus, ${\mathbb {N} }\to {\mathbb {R} }$ is the type of functions from natural numbers to real numbers.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Such Π-types correspond to logical implication.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] The logical proposition $A\implies B$ corresponds to the type $A\to B$ , containing functions that take proofs-of-A and return proofs-of-B.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Π-types are also used in logic for universal quantification.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] The statement "for every n of type ${\mathbb {N} }$ , $P(n)$ is proven" becomes a function from n of type ${\mathbb {N} }$ to proofs of $P(n)$ .
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Thus, given the value for n the function generates a proof that $P(\,\cdot \,)$ holds for that value.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Given two terms like $2+2$ and $2\cdot 2$ , you can create a new type $2+2=2\cdot 2$ .
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] The terms of that new type represent proofs that the pair reduce to the same canonical term.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Thus, since both $2+2$ and $2\cdot 2$ compute to the canonical term 4 , there will be a term of the type $2+2=2\cdot 2$ .
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] It is possible to create =-types such as $1=2$ where the terms do not reduce to the same canonical term, but you will be unable to create terms of that new type.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] In fact, if you were able to create a term of $1=2$ , you could create a term of $\bot$ .
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Putting that into a function would generate a function of type $1=2\to \bot$ .
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Since $\ldots \to \bot$ is how intuitionistic type theory defines negation, you would have $\neg (1=2)$ or, finally, $1\neq 2$ .
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Equality of proofs is an area of active research in proof theory and has led to the development of homotopy type theory and other type theories.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Inductive types allow the creation of complex, self-referential types.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] For example, a linked list of natural numbers is either an empty list or a pair of a natural number and another linked list.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Inductive types can be used to define unbounded mathematical structures like trees, graphs, etc..
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] In fact, the natural numbers type may be defined as an inductive type, either being 0 or the successor of another natural number.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Inductive types define new constants, such as zero $0{\mathbin {:}}{\mathbb {N} }$ and the successor function $S{\mathbin {:}}{\mathbb {N} }\to {\mathbb {N} }$ .
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Since S does not have a definition and cannot be evaluated using substitution, terms like $S0$ and $SSS0$ become the canonical terms of the natural numbers.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Proofs on inductive types are made possible by induction.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Each new inductive type comes with its own inductive rule.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Inductive types in intuitionistic type theory are defined in terms of W-types, the type of well-founded trees.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Later work in type theory generated coinductive types, induction-recursion, and induction-induction for working on types with more obscure kinds of self-referentiality.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Higher inductive types allow equality to be defined between terms.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] The universe types allow proofs to be written about all the types created with the other type constructors.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Every term in the universe type ${\mathcal {U}}_{0}$ can be mapped to a type created with any combination of $0,1,2,\Sigma ,\Pi ,=,$ and the inductive type constructor.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] However, to avoid paradoxes, there is no term in ${\mathcal {U}}_{n}$ that maps to ${\mathcal {U}}_{n}$ for any ${\mathcal {n}}\in \mathbb {N}$ .
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] To write proofs about all "the small types" and ${\mathcal {U}}_{0}$ , you must use ${\mathcal {U}}_{1}$ , which does contain a term for ${\mathcal {U}}_{0}$ , but not for itself ${\mathcal {U}}_{1}$ .
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] There is a predicative hierarchy of universes, so to quantify a proof over any fixed constant k universes, you can use ${\mathcal {U}}_{k+1}$ .
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Universe types are a tricky feature of type theories.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Martin-Löf's original type theory had to be changed to account for Girard's paradox.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Later research covered topics such as "super universes", "Mahlo universes", and impredicative universes.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] The formal definition of intuitionistic type theory is written using judgements.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] For example, in the statement "if A is a type and B is a type then $\textstyle \sum _{a:A}B$ is a type" there are judgements of "is a type", "and", and "if ... then ...".
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] The expression $\textstyle \sum _{a:A}B$ is not a judgement; it is the type being defined.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] This second level of the type theory can be confusing, particularly where it comes to equality.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] There is a judgement of term equality, which might say $4=2+2$ .
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] It is a statement that two terms reduce to the same canonical term.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] There is also a judgement of type equality, say that $A=B$ , which means every element of A is an element of the type B and vice versa.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] At the type level, there is a type $4=2+2$ and it contains terms if there is a proof that 4 and $2+2$ reduce to the same value.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] (Terms of this type are generated using the term-equality judgement.) Lastly, there is an English-language level of equality, because we use the word "four" and symbol " 4 " to refer to the canonical term $SSSS0$ .
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Synonyms like these are called "definitionally equal" by Martin-Löf.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] The description of judgements below is based on the discussion in Nordström, Petersson, and Smith.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] The formal theory works with *types* and *objects*.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] An object that depends on an object from another type can be done two ways.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] The object-depending-on-object can also be declared as a constant as part of a recursive type.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Here, S is a constant object-depending-on-object.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] It is not associated with an abstraction.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Constants like S can be removed by defining equality.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] S is manipulated as an opaque constant - it has no internal structure for substitution.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] So, objects and types and these relations are used to express formulae in the theory.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] By convention, there is a type that represents all other types.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] It is called ${\mathcal {U}}$ (or $\operatorname {Set}$ ).
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Since ${\mathcal {U}}$ is a type, the members of it are objects.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] There is a dependent type $\operatorname {El}$ that maps each object to its corresponding type.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] *In most texts $\operatorname {El}$ is never written.* From the context of the statement, a reader can almost always tell whether A refers to a type, or whether it refers to the object in ${\mathcal {U}}$ that corresponds to the type.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] This is the complete foundation of the theory.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] To implement logic, each proposition is given its own type.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] The objects in those types represent the different possible ways to prove the proposition.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] If there is no proof for the proposition, then the type has no objects in it.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Operators like "and" and "or" that work on propositions introduce new types and new objects.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] So $A\times B$ is a type that depends on the type A and the type B .
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] The objects in that dependent type are defined to exist for every pair of objects in A and B .
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] If either A or B have no proof and is an empty type, then the new type representing $A\times B$ is also empty.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] This can be done for other types (booleans, natural numbers, etc.) and their operators.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Using the language of category theory, R.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Seely introduced the notion of a locally cartesian closed category (LCCC) as the basic model of type theory.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] This has been refined by Hofmann and Dybjer to Categories with Families or *Categories with Attributes* based on earlier work by Cartmell.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] A fundamental distinction is extensional vs intensional type theory.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] In extensional type theory, definitional (i.e., computational) equality is not distinguished from propositional equality, which requires proof.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] As a consequence type checking becomes undecidable in extensional type theory because programs in the theory might not terminate.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] For example, such a theory allows one to give a type to the Y-combinator; a detailed example of this can be found in Nordstöm and Petersson *Programming in Martin-Löf's Type Theory*.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] However, this does not prevent extensional type theory from being a basis for a practical tool; for example, Nuprl is based on extensional type theory.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] In contrast, in intensional type theory type checking is decidable, but the representation of standard mathematical concepts is somewhat more cumbersome, since intensional reasoning requires using setoids or similar constructions.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] There are many common mathematical objects that are hard to work with or cannot be represented without this, for example, integer numbers, rational numbers, and real numbers.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Integers and rational numbers can be represented without setoids, but this representation is difficult to work with.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Cauchy real numbers cannot be represented without this.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Homotopy type theory works on resolving this problem.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] It allows one to define higher inductive types, which not only define first-order constructors (values or points), but higher-order constructors, i.e. equalities between elements (paths), equalities between equalities (homotopies), *ad infinitum*.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Different forms of type theory have been implemented as the formal systems underlying a number of proof assistants.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] While many are based on Per Martin-Löf's ideas, many have added features, more axioms, or a different philosophical background.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] For instance, the Nuprl system is based on computational type theory and Rocq is based on the calculus of (co)inductive constructions.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Dependent types also feature in the design of programming languages such as ATS, Cayenne, Epigram, Agda, and Idris.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] Per Martin-Löf constructed several type theories that were published at various times, some of them much later than when the preprints with their description became accessible to specialists (among others Jean-Yves Girard and Giovanni Sambin).
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] The list below attempts to list all the theories that have been described in a printed form and to sketch the key features that distinguished them from each other.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] All of these theories had dependent products, dependent sums, disjoint unions, finite types and natural numbers.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/intuitionistic-type-theory] All the theories had the same reduction rules that did not include η-reduction either for dependent products or for dependent sums, except for MLTT79 where the η-reduction for dependent products is added.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/proof-assistant] In computer science and mathematical logic, a **proof assistant** or **interactive theorem prover** is a software tool to assist with the development of formal proofs by human–machine collaboration.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/proof-assistant] This involves some sort of interactive proof editor, or other interface, with which a human can guide the search for proofs, the details of which are stored in, and some steps provided by, a computer.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/proof-assistant] A recent effort within this field is making these tools use artificial intelligence to automate the formalization of ordinary mathematics.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/proof-assistant] Because of this small size, some automated proof checking systems can have less than a thousand lines of core code, and are thus themselves amenable to both hand-checking and automated software verification.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/proof-assistant] The Mizar system, HOL Light, and Metamath are examples of automated proof checking systems.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/proof-assistant] Automated proof checking can be done either as a batch operation, or interactively, as part of an interactive theorem proving system.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/proof-assistant] Automath, which was developed by Nicolaas Govert de Bruijn starting in 1967, is often considered the first proof checker and the first system to utilize the Curry–Howard correspondence between programs and proofs.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/proof-assistant] Automath was used by L.S. van Benthem Jutting in 1977 to formalize Landau's *Foundations of Analysis*, which was the first formalization of the real numbers.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/proof-assistant] In 1973, Robert Boyer and J Moore published *Proving Theorems about LISP Functions* which aimed to verify programs, not mathematics.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/proof-assistant] Their theorem prover is now known as ACL2.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/proof-assistant] In the 1970s, Edinburgh LCF introduced the idea of using a functional programming language as the metalanguage for a theorem prover, and led to the HOL family of proof assistants.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/proof-assistant] The 1990s saw the rise of Rocq, (then known as Coq), which has been used for many large-scale formalization projects.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/proof-assistant] Since the late 2010s, Lean, a proof assistant strongly influenced by Rocq, has become another popular choice, especially for formalizing mathematics.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/proof-assistant] A commonly used front-end for proof assistants was the Emacs-based Proof General, developed at the University of Edinburgh.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/proof-assistant] Nowadays, many provers include their own editor.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/proof-assistant] Rocq includes RocqIDE, which is based on OCaml/Gtk.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/proof-assistant] Isabelle includes Isabelle/jEdit, which is based on jEdit and the Isabelle/Scala infrastructure for document-oriented proof processing.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/proof-assistant] More recently, Visual Studio Code extensions have been developed for Rocq, Isabelle by Makarius Wenzel, and for Lean 4 by the leanprover developers.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/proof-assistant] Freek Wiedijk has been keeping a ranking of proof assistants by the amount of formalized theorems out of a list of 100 well-known theorems.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/proof-assistant] As of September 2025, only six systems have formalized proofs of more than 70% of the theorems, namely Isabelle, HOL Light, Lean, Rocq, Metamath and Mizar.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/proof-assistant] The following is a list of notable proofs that have been formalized within proof assistants.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] Univalent foundations are compatible with structuralism, if an appropriate (i.e., categorical) notion of mathematical structure is adopted.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] The main ideas of univalent foundations were formulated by Vladimir Voevodsky during the years 2006 to 2009.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] The sole reference for the philosophical connections between univalent foundations and earlier ideas are Voevodsky's 2014 Bernays lectures.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] The name "univalence" is due to Voevodsky.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] A more detailed discussion of the history of some of the ideas that contribute to the current state of univalent foundations can be found at the page on homotopy type theory (HoTT).
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] A fundamental characteristic of univalent foundations is that they—when combined with the Martin-Löf type theory (MLTT)—provide a practical system for formalization of modern mathematics.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] A considerable amount of mathematics has been formalized using this system and modern proof assistants such as Rocq (previously known as *Coq*) and Agda.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] The first such library called "Foundations" was created by Vladimir Voevodsky in 2010.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] Now Foundations is a part of a larger development with several authors called UniMath.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] Foundations also inspired other libraries of formalized mathematics, such as the HoTT Coq library and HoTT Agda library, that developed univalent ideas in new directions.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] An important milestone for univalent foundations was the Bourbaki Seminar talk by Thierry Coquand in June 2014.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] Univalent foundations originated from certain attempts to create foundations of mathematics based on higher category theory.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] The closest earlier ideas to univalent foundations were the ideas that Michael Makkai denotes 'first-order logic with dependent sorts' (FOLDS).
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] The main distinction between univalent foundations and the foundations envisioned by Makkai is the recognition that "higher dimensional analogs of sets" correspond to infinity groupoids and that categories should be considered as higher-dimensional analogs of partially ordered sets.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] Originally, univalent foundations were devised by Vladimir Voevodsky with the goal of enabling those who work in classical pure mathematics to use computers to verify their theorems and constructions.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] The fact that univalent foundations are inherently constructive was discovered in the process of writing the Foundations library (now part of UniMath).
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] In the formalization system for univalent foundations that is based on Martin-Löf type theory and its descendants such as Calculus of Inductive Constructions, the higher dimensional analogs of sets are represented by types.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] The collection of types is stratified by the concept of *h-level* (or *homotopy level*).
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] Types of h-level 0 are those equal to the one point type.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] They are also called contractible types.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] Types of h-level 1 are those in which any two elements are equal.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] Such types are called "propositions" in univalent foundations.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] The definition of propositions in terms of the h-level agrees with the definition suggested earlier by Awodey and Bauer.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] So, while all propositions are types, not all types are propositions.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] Being a proposition is a property of a type that requires proof.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] For example, the first fundamental construction in univalent foundations is called **iscontr**.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] If **X** is a type then **iscontr X** is a type that has an object if and only if **X** is contractible.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] It is a theorem (which is called, in the UniMath library, **isapropiscontr**) that for any **X** the type **iscontr X** has h-level 1 and therefore being a contractible type is a property.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] This distinction between properties that are witnessed by objects of types of h-level 1 and structures that are witnessed by objects of types of higher h-levels is very important in the univalent foundations.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] It is a theorem that the type of natural numbers has h-level 2 (**isasetnat** in UniMath).
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] It is claimed by the creators of univalent foundations that the univalent formalization of sets in Martin-Löf type theory is the best currently-available environment for formal reasoning about all aspects of set-theoretical mathematics, both constructive and classical.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] Categories are defined (see the RezkCompletion library in UniMath) as types of h-level 3 with an additional structure that is very similar to the structure on types of h-level 2 that defines partially ordered sets.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] The theory of categories in univalent foundations is somewhat different and richer than the theory of categories in the set-theoretic world with the key new distinction being that between pre-categories and categories.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] An account of the main ideas of univalent foundations and their connection to constructive mathematics can be found in a tutorial by Thierry Coquand.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] A presentation of the main ideas from the perspective of classical mathematics can be found in the 2014 review by Alvaro Pelayo and Michael Warren, as well as in the introduction by Daniel Grayson.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] An account of Voevodsky's construction of a univalent model of the Martin-Löf type theory with values in Kan simplicial sets can be found in a paper by Chris Kapulkin, Peter LeFanu Lumsdaine and Vladimir Voevodsky.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] Univalent models with values in the categories of inverse diagrams of simplicial sets were constructed by Michael Shulman.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] These models have shown that the univalence axiom is independent from the excluded middle axiom for propositions.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] Voevodsky's model is considered to be non-constructive since it uses the axiom of choice in an ineliminable way.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] The problem of finding a constructive interpretation of the rules of the Martin-Löf type theory that in addition satisfies the univalence axiom and canonicity for natural numbers remains open.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] A partial solution is outlined in a paper by Marc Bezem, Thierry Coquand and Simon Huber with the key remaining issue being the computational property of the eliminator for the identity types.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] The ideas of this paper are now being developed in several directions including the development of the cubical type theory.
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] Most of the work on formalization of mathematics in the framework of univalent foundations is being done using various sub-systems and extensions of the Calculus of Inductive Constructions (CIC).
[src:homotopy-type-theory/univalent-foundations] To extend CIC with a universe management system that would allow implementation of the resizing rules.
